A component is just a JavaScript function that returns HTML.

Basic Component:
function Welcome() {
  return Hello, World;
}

Using a Component:
function App() {
  return (
    div
      Welcome
      Welcome
      Welcome
    div
  );
}

Key Rules:
1. Component names must start with uppercase
2. Components must return a single root element
3. Components are reusable - use them as many times as needed

Your First Interactive Component:
function Greeting() {
  const name = Student;
  return h1Hello, {name};/h1;
}

Notice the curly braces - they are for embedding JavaScript in JSX.

JSX is a syntax extension for JavaScript that lets you write HTML-like code in your JavaScript files.

Why JSX?
- More readable than createElement
- Combines UI logic with component logic
- Familiar syntax for web developers

JSX Rules:
1. Return a single element (or use fragments)
2. Close all tags (including self-closing like img /)
3. Use camelCase for attributes (onClick, className)
4. Use curly braces for JavaScript expressions

Examples:
// JavaScript expressions in JSX
const name = Alice;
const element = h1Hello, {name.toUpperCase()}!/h1;

// Conditional rendering
const isLoggedIn = true;
return (
  div
    {isLoggedIn ? h1Welcome back!/h1 : h1Please log in/h1}
  /div
);

State is data that changes over time in your application. When state changes, React automatically updates the UI to reflect the new data.

What is State?
- Data that can change
- Triggers UI updates when modified
- Local to each component

Why State Matters:
Without state, your app would be static - nothing would ever change or respond to user actions.

Simple State Example:
import { useState } from react;

function Counter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  return (
    button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}Clicked {count} times/button
  );
}

The key parts:
1. useState(0) - Initializes state with value 0
2. count - The current value
3. setCount - Function to update the value (only way to change state)

The Hook Pattern:
const [state, setState] = useState(initialValue);

- state - The current value (like a variable)
- setState - Function to update the value (only way to change state)
- useState - The hook that creates state
- initialValue - Starting value for the state

Multiple State Values:
function Form() {
  const [name, setName] = useState();
  const [email, setEmail] = useState();
  const [age, setAge] = useState(0);

  return (
    form
      input value={name} onChange={e => setName(e.target.value)} /
      input value={email} onChange={e => setEmail(e.target.value)} /
    /form
  );
}

Common Mistake:
WRONG: count = count + 1;
CORRECT: setCount(count + 1);
BEST: setCount(prevCount => prevCount + 1);

When to Use State:
- User input (form fields, selections)
- Toggle states (on/off, open/closed)
- Counts and numbers
- Loading states
- Error messages

When NOT to Use State:
- Derived data (calculate from other state)
- Static data that never changes
- Data that does not affect UI

Object State:
const [user, setUser] = useState({
  name: ,
  email: ,
  age: 0
});

// Updating object state - spread operator
setUser(prev => ({...prev, name: John}));

Array State:
const [items, setItems] = useState([]);

// Add item
setItems(prev => [...prev, newItem]);

// Remove item
setItems(prev => prev.filter(item => item.id !== id));

Side effects are anything that happens outside of rendering - things that do not directly produce UI output.

Examples of Side Effects:
- Fetching data from an API
- Setting up subscriptions
- Updating the document title
- Starting timers
- Logging to console

Why Special Handling?
React components should be pure - same inputs always produce same output. But we need side effects for real apps.

The useEffect Hook:
useEffect lets you run side effects in function components.

import { useEffect } from react;

function MyComponent() {
  useEffect(() => {
    console.log(Component rendered!);
  });
}

The dependency array controls when useEffect runs:

No Dependencies [] - Run Once:
useEffect(() => {
  console.log(Runs only on mount);
}, []);

With Dependencies [data] - Run When Changed:
useEffect(() => {
  console.log(Runs when count changes);
}, [count]);

No Array - Run Every Render:
useEffect(() => {
  console.log(Runs after every render);
});

Common Patterns:

// Fetch data on mount
useEffect(() => {
  fetch(/api/data).then(res => res.json());
}, []);

// Run when userId changes
useEffect(() => {
  fetchUser(userId).then(setUser);
}, [userId]);

// Cleanup on unmount
useEffect(() => {
  const subscription = subscribe(id);
  return () => subscription.unsubscribe();
}, [id]);

Here is how to fetch data in React:

function UserProfile(userId) {
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
  const [error, setError] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    async function fetchUser() {
      try {
        setLoading(true);
        const response = await fetch(`/api/users/${userId}`);
        const data = await response.json();
        setUser(data);
      } catch (err) {
        setError(err.message);
      } finally {
        setLoading(false);
      }
    }

    fetchUser();
  }, [userId]);

  if (loading) return pLoading.../p;
  if (error) return pError: {error}/p;
  if (!user) return null;

  return (
    div
      h1{user.name}/h1
      p{user.email}/p
    /div
  );
}

Important: Always handle loading and error states.

A stack is a linear data structure that follows the Last In First Out (LIFO) principle. Think of a stack of plates - you can only add or remove from the top.

Real-World Examples:
- Undo/Redo in editors
- Browser history (back button)
- Function call stack in programming
- Stack of cards

Operations:
- push(item) - Add to top: O(1)
- pop() - Remove from top: O(1)
- peek() - View top without removing: O(1)
- isEmpty() - Check if empty: O(1)

Implementation:
class Stack {
  constructor() {
    this.items = [];
  }

  push(item) {
    this.items.push(item);
  }

  pop() {
    return this.items.pop();
  }

  peek() {
    return this.items[this.items.length - 1];
  }
}

Stack Applications:

1. Expression Evaluation
- Converting infix to postfix
- Evaluating postfix expressions

2. Function Call Stack
- Managing function calls
- Recursion

3. Parentheses Matching
function isBalanced(str) {
  const stack = new Stack();
  const pairs = { ): (, }: {, ]: [ };

  for (const char of str) {
    if (({[.includes(char)) {
      stack.push(char);
    } else if ()}].includes(char)) {
      if (stack.isEmpty() || stack.pop() !== pairs[char]) {
        return false;
      }
    }
  }
  return stack.isEmpty();
}

Queue Applications:

1. BFS (Breadth-First Search)
- Level-order tree traversal
- Finding shortest path in unweighted graphs

2. Task Scheduling
- Print queue
- CPU task scheduling

A Binary Search Tree (BST) is a binary tree where:
- Left subtree contains only nodes with values less than parent
- Right subtree contains only nodes with values greater than parent
- Both subtrees are also BSTs

Operations (Average Case):
- Search: O(log n)
- Insert: O(log n)
- Delete: O(log n)

Implementation:
class BSTNode {
  constructor(value) {
    this.value = value;
    this.left = null;
    this.right = null;
  }
}

class BST {
  constructor() {
    this.root = null;
  }

  insert(value) {
    const newNode = new BSTNode(value);

    if (!this.root) {
      this.root = newNode;
      return this;
    }

    let current = this.root;
    while (true) {
      if (value < current.value) {
        if (!current.left) {
          current.left = newNode;
          return this;
        }
        current = current.left;
      } else {
        if (!current.right) {
          current.right = newNode;
          return this;
        }
        current = current.right;
      }
    }
  }
}

There are several ways to traverse (visit all nodes) in a tree:

1. Depth-First Search (DFS)

Inorder (Left, Root, Right):
function inorder(node) {
  if (!node) return;
  inorder(node.left);
  console.log(node.value);
  inorder(node.right);
}
// BST inorder gives sorted order

Preorder (Root, Left, Right):
function preorder(node) {
  if (!node) return;
  console.log(node.value);
  preorder(node.left);
  preorder(node.right);
}

2. Breadth-First Search (BFS)

function bfs(root) {
  if (!root) return;
  const queue = [root];

  while (queue.length) {
    const node = queue.shift();
    console.log(node.value);
    if (node.left) queue.push(node.left);
    if (node.right) queue.push(node.right);
  }
}

When to Use Which?
- Inorder: BST sorted order
- Preorder: Copy/serialize tree
- Postorder: Delete tree (children first)
- BFS: Level-order, shortest path
